  "prompt": "If I deposit 9 lakhs by cheque into my saving account and withdraws it the same day, will the transaction come under IT notice?",
  "response": "Depositing and withdrawing large amounts of money in a short period of time can potentially attract the attention of tax authorities, such as the Income Tax Department in India. However, whether a specific transaction will trigger an investigation or notice can depend on several factors:\n\n1. **Threshold Limits**: Banks are required to report certain transactions above specified thresholds to tax authorities. For savings accounts, cash deposits or withdrawals of \u20b910 lakh or more in a financial year are generally reported.\n\n2. **Consistency with Your Financial Profile**: If such transactions are consistent with your known income, business activities, or past transactions, this might not raise concerns. However, if your account activity is generally low or not consistent with large transactions, it might draw attention.\n\n3. **Source of Funds**: The source of the funds can be a factor. If the deposit is from a legitimate and traceable source and you can justify it, there may be no issue.\n\n4. **Purpose and Frequency**: Frequent large transactions, especially withdrawals immediately after deposits without a clear purpose, could appear suspicious.\n\nAlthough depositing and withdrawing \u20b99 lakhs in one day might not automatically lead to a notice, it is close to the reporting thresholds, and if there are multiple such transactions, or if the pattern seems unusual for your account, it could come under scrutiny.\n\nIt\u2019s always a good idea to maintain clear records of transactions and ensure all tax obligations are met. If you're concerned about attracting attention from tax authorities, consider consulting with a tax professional who can provide guidance based on the current regulations and your specific situation.",
